{"id": "hist-magellan-circumnavigation-146", "type": "fact", "statement": "Ferdinand Magellan's expedition (1519–1522) achieved the first circumnavigation of the Earth, though Magellan himself was killed in the Philippines.", "explanation": "Magellan set sail from Spain with five ships; only one, the Victoria, completed the journey under Juan Sebastián Elcano with 18 surviving crew, proving the Earth's roundness and the vastness of the Pacific.", "quizQuestion": "Who completed the first circumnavigation of the Earth after Magellan's death?", "correctAnswer": "Juan Sebastián Elcano", "distractors": ["Sir Francis Drake", "Vasco da Gama", "Christopher Columbus", "James Cook"], "variants": [{"question": "In what year did Magellan's expedition depart?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "1519", "distractors": ["1492", "1498", "1534"]}, {"question": "What was the name of the only ship to complete the circumnavigation?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Victoria", "distractors": ["Santa María", "Endeavour", "Golden Hind"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 3, "funScore": 8, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art wooden sailing ship with tattered sails crossing a vast blue ocean, a globe icon overlaid showing the completed route circling the Earth.", "tags": ["history", "age-of-exploration", "circumnavigation", "spain"]}
{"id": "hist-pompeii-eruption-147", "type": "fact", "statement": "The eruption of Mount Vesuvius in 79 CE buried the Roman cities of Pompeii and Herculaneum under volcanic ash.", "explanation": "The catastrophic eruption preserved the cities in remarkable detail, providing modern archaeologists an extraordinary snapshot of Roman daily life, from frescoes and graffiti to bread still in ovens.", "quizQuestion": "Which volcano destroyed Pompeii in 79 CE?", "correctAnswer": "Mount Vesuvius", "distractors": ["Mount Etna", "Mount Olympus", "Mount Stromboli", "Mount Olympus"], "variants": [{"question": "Besides Pompeii, what other city was buried by Vesuvius?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Herculaneum", "distractors": ["Carthage", "Ostia", "Syracuse"]}, {"question": "In what century did the eruption that buried Pompeii occur?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "1st century CE", "distractors": ["3rd century BCE", "5th century CE", "2nd century BCE"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 2, "funScore": 9, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art erupting volcano spewing dark ash over a terraced Roman city with red-roofed villas, frozen figures in the streets, and a glowing lava flow in the distance.", "tags": ["history", "archaeology", "ancient-rome", "natural-disasters"]}
{"id": "hist-industrial-revolution-148", "type": "fact", "statement": "The Industrial Revolution began in Britain around 1760, transforming manufacturing from hand production to machine-based processes.", "explanation": "Starting with innovations in textile manufacturing and powered by steam engines, the Industrial Revolution urbanized Britain, created factory systems, and spread globally, fundamentally changing economies and societies.", "quizQuestion": "In which country did the Industrial Revolution begin?", "correctAnswer": "Britain", "distractors": ["France", "Germany", "United States", "Germany"], "variants": [{"question": "Around what year did the Industrial Revolution begin?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "1760", "distractors": ["1820", "1700", "1850"]}, {"question": "What power source drove early Industrial Revolution factories?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Steam engines", "distractors": ["Electric motors", "Water wheels only", "Wind turbines"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 1, "funScore": 6, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art scene of a smoky British factory town with tall brick chimneys belching steam, workers entering a textile mill, and a canal with barges in the foreground.", "tags": ["history", "industrial-revolution", "britain", "manufacturing", "inventions"]}
{"id": "hist-enigma-code-149", "type": "fact", "statement": "Alan Turing and the team at Bletchley Park cracked the German Enigma code during World War II, shortening the war by an estimated two years.", "explanation": "The Enigma machine was considered unbreakable by Germany. Turing built the Bombe, an electro-mechanical device that rapidly tested Enigma settings, giving the Allies vital intelligence known as Ultra.", "quizQuestion": "What was the name of the electro-mechanical device Turing built to crack Enigma?", "correctAnswer": "The Bombe", "distractors": ["The Colossus", "The ENIAC", "The Difference Engine", "The Babbage Engine"], "variants": [{"question": "At which facility was the Enigma code broken?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Bletchley Park", "distractors": ["Los Alamos", "Pentagon", "Langley"]}, {"question": "By how many years did breaking Enigma reportedly shorten WWII?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Two years", "distractors": ["Six months", "Five years", "One year"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 3, "funScore": 9, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art room filled with rows of mechanical Bombe machines whirring and clicking, with a bespectacled codebreaker studying paper tape output at a cluttered desk.", "tags": ["history", "wwii", "espionage", "codebreaking", "inventions"]}
{"id": "hist-terracotta-army-150", "type": "fact", "statement": "The Terracotta Army, discovered in 1974 near Xi'an, China, consists of over 8,000 life-sized clay soldiers guarding Emperor Qin Shi Huang's tomb.", "explanation": "Created around 210 BCE, each figure has unique facial features. The army was built to protect the first emperor of unified China in the afterlife and is considered one of the greatest archaeological discoveries.", "quizQuestion": "How many terracotta soldiers are estimated to be in the Terracotta Army?", "correctAnswer": "Over 8,000", "distractors": ["About 2,000", "Roughly 500", "Around 15,000", "Roughly 500"], "variants": [{"question": "Which emperor's tomb does the Terracotta Army guard?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Qin Shi Huang", "distractors": ["Emperor Wu", "Kublai Khan", "Emperor Taizong"]}, {"question": "In what year was the Terracotta Army discovered?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "1974", "distractors": ["1922", "1952", "1999"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 2, "funScore": 9, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art underground excavation pit revealing rows upon rows of clay warriors in battle formation, each with distinct armor and expressions, illuminated by overhead floodlights.", "tags": ["history", "archaeology", "ancient-china", "ancient-technology"]}
{"id": "hist-cold-war-berlin-wall-151", "type": "fact", "statement": "The Berlin Wall stood from 1961 to 1989, dividing East and West Berlin during the Cold War.", "explanation": "Built by East Germany to prevent citizens from fleeing to the West, the Wall became the most potent symbol of the Iron Curtain. Its fall on November 9, 1989, marked the beginning of German reunification.", "quizQuestion": "In what year did the Berlin Wall fall?", "correctAnswer": "1989", "distractors": ["1991", "1985", "1979", "1975"], "variants": [{"question": "In what year was the Berlin Wall constructed?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "1961", "distractors": ["1949", "1955", "1968"]}, {"question": "What did the Berlin Wall symbolize during the Cold War?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "The Iron Curtain dividing East and West", "distractors": ["NATO expansion", "The space race", "Nuclear disarmament"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 1, "funScore": 8, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art concrete wall topped with barbed wire cutting through a city, graffiti on the western side, watchtowers and searchlights on the eastern side, crowds gathering with hammers.", "tags": ["history", "cold-war", "germany", "berlin", "modern"]}
{"id": "hist-suffragettes-152", "type": "fact", "statement": "New Zealand became the first self-governing country to grant women the right to vote in 1893.", "explanation": "The campaign was led by Kate Sheppard, who organized a massive petition. New Zealand's decision preceded similar rights in Australia (1902), Finland (1906), and the UK/US (1918/1920).", "quizQuestion": "Which country first granted women the right to vote in national elections?", "correctAnswer": "New Zealand", "distractors": ["United Kingdom", "United States", "France", "Australia"], "variants": [{"question": "Who led New Zealand's women's suffrage movement?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Kate Sheppard", "distractors": ["Emmeline Pankhurst", "Susan B. Anthony", "Sojourner Truth"]}, {"question": "In what year did New Zealand grant women's suffrage?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "1893", "distractors": ["1901", "1920", "1848"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 3, "funScore": 7, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art rally scene with women in Victorian dress carrying banners reading 'Votes for Women' outside a grand parliament building with a New Zealand flag.", "tags": ["history", "women-in-history", "civil-rights", "suffrage"]}
{"id": "hist-sputnik-launch-153", "type": "fact", "statement": "The Soviet Union launched Sputnik 1, the first artificial satellite, on October 4, 1957, igniting the Space Race.", "explanation": "Sputnik was a 58-cm polished metal sphere that orbited Earth transmitting radio beeps for 21 days. Its launch shocked the United States and led directly to the creation of NASA in 1958.", "quizQuestion": "What was the name of the first artificial satellite launched into orbit?", "correctAnswer": "Sputnik 1", "distractors": ["Explorer 1", "Vanguard 1", "Luna 1", "Gemini 1"], "variants": [{"question": "Which country launched the first artificial satellite?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "The Soviet Union", "distractors": ["The United States", "China", "France"]}, {"question": "What agency did the US create in response to Sputnik?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "NASA", "distractors": ["DARPA", "CIA", "ESA"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 2, "funScore": 8, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art night sky with a small shiny metal sphere trailing four antennas orbiting above a curved Earth horizon, radio wave circles emanating from the satellite.", "tags": ["history", "space-race", "cold-war", "soviet-union", "inventions"]}
{"id": "hist-spanish-flu-154", "type": "fact", "statement": "The 1918 Spanish flu pandemic infected roughly one-third of the world's population and killed an estimated 50–100 million people.", "explanation": "Despite its name, the flu likely originated in the United States or Europe. Spain, being neutral in WWI, reported freely on the outbreak, giving it the misleading name. It was an H1N1 influenza virus.", "quizQuestion": "Approximately what fraction of the world's population was infected by the 1918 flu?", "correctAnswer": "One-third", "distractors": ["One-tenth", "Half", "One-quarter", "One-fifth"], "variants": [{"question": "What type of virus caused the 1918 pandemic?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "H1N1 influenza", "distractors": ["Smallpox", "Cholera", "Bubonic plague"]}, {"question": "Why was the 1918 pandemic called 'Spanish' flu?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Spain reported freely on it while warring nations censored news", "distractors": ["It originated in Spain", "Spanish doctors discovered it", "Spain was hit hardest"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 3, "funScore": 6, "ageRating": "teen", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art 1918 hospital ward with rows of beds filled with patients, nurses in white masks and uniforms tending to them, Red Cross flags visible through windows.", "tags": ["history", "pandemics", "wwi", "disease", "modern"]}
{"id": "hist-antikythera-mechanism-155", "type": "fact", "statement": "The Antikythera Mechanism, dating to around 100 BCE, is the oldest known analog computer, used to predict astronomical positions.", "explanation": "Recovered from a Roman-era shipwreck off the Greek island of Antikythera in 1901, this intricate bronze device contained at least 30 meshing gears and could track the movements of the Sun, Moon, and planets.", "quizQuestion": "What was the Antikythera Mechanism used to predict?", "correctAnswer": "Astronomical positions", "distractors": ["Weather patterns", "Earthquake timing", "Ocean tides", "Navigation routes"], "variants": [{"question": "From what type of site was the Antikythera Mechanism recovered?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "A shipwreck", "distractors": ["A temple", "A tomb", "A battlefield"]}, {"question": "Approximately how many gears did the Antikythera Mechanism contain?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "At least 30", "distractors": ["About 5", "Over 100", "Exactly 12"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 4, "funScore": 10, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art corroded bronze mechanism with visible interlocking gears and dials, displayed against a dark underwater backdrop with coral and fish swimming past.", "tags": ["history", "ancient-technology", "archaeology", "greece", "inventions"]}
{"id": "hist-mongol-empire-156", "type": "fact", "statement": "The Mongol Empire under Genghis Khan became the largest contiguous land empire in history, spanning 24 million km² at its peak.", "explanation": "Founded in 1206, the empire stretched from Korea to Hungary. Genghis Khan introduced the Yasa legal code, a meritocratic military system, and a postal relay network (Yam) that connected the vast empire.", "quizQuestion": "What was the approximate area of the Mongol Empire at its peak?", "correctAnswer": "24 million km²", "distractors": ["10 million km²", "36 million km²", "5 million km²", "15 million km²"], "variants": [{"question": "In what year was the Mongol Empire founded?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "1206", "distractors": ["1066", "1299", "1162"]}, {"question": "What was the Mongol postal relay system called?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Yam", "distractors": ["Pony Express", "Cursus publicus", "Angareion"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 3, "funScore": 8, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art vast steppe landscape with Mongol horsemen galloping beneath yurt-dotted hills, a massive empire map spreading behind them in warm earth tones.", "tags": ["history", "mongol-empire", "medieval", "military", "famous-battles"]}
{"id": "hist-galileo-trial-157", "type": "fact", "statement": "Galileo Galilei was tried by the Roman Inquisition in 1633 for advocating the heliocentric model of the solar system.", "explanation": "Galileo's telescopic observations of Jupiter's moons and Venus's phases supported Copernicus's theory that the Earth orbited the Sun. The Church found him 'vehemently suspect of heresy' and placed him under house arrest for life.", "quizQuestion": "Why was Galileo tried by the Roman Inquisition?", "correctAnswer": "For advocating the heliocentric model", "distractors": ["For practicing alchemy", "For denying the Trinity", "For publishing unauthorized Bibles", "For challenging the Pope's authority"], "variants": [{"question": "What punishment did Galileo receive from the Inquisition?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "House arrest for life", "distractors": ["Execution", "Exile", "Imprisonment for ten years"]}, {"question": "Whose theory did Galileo's observations support?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Copernicus", "distractors": ["Ptolemy", "Aristotle", "Kepler"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 3, "funScore": 8, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art courtroom scene with a bearded Galileo standing before robed Inquisition officials, a telescope and astronomical charts on a table between them.", "tags": ["history", "scientific-revolutions", "renaissance", "astronomy", "trial"]}
{"id": "hist-trojan-horse-158", "type": "fact", "statement": "According to ancient Greek tradition, the Greeks used a giant wooden horse to infiltrate and capture the city of Troy around 1184 BCE.", "explanation": "After a ten-year siege, the Greeks hid soldiers inside a massive wooden horse left as a false offering. The Trojans brought it inside their walls, and at night the hidden Greeks opened the gates, ending the war.", "quizQuestion": "What trick did the Greeks allegedly use to capture Troy?", "correctAnswer": "A giant wooden horse with soldiers hidden inside", "distractors": ["A tunnel beneath the walls", "A poisoned water supply", "A fake peace treaty and ambush", "A massive battering ram"], "variants": [{"question": "How long did the legendary siege of Troy last?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Ten years", "distractors": ["Three years", "One year", "Twenty years"]}, {"question": "The story of the Trojan Horse comes from which literary tradition?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Ancient Greek", "distractors": ["Roman", "Persian", "Egyptian"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 1, "funScore": 9, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art massive wooden horse on wheels being pulled through towering stone gates by unsuspecting Trojans, torchlight flickering on the city walls at dusk.", "tags": ["history", "classical-antiquity", "famous-battles", "mythology", "greece"]}
{"id": "hist-d-day-normandy-159", "type": "fact", "statement": "D-Day on June 6, 1944, was the largest seaborne invasion in history, with over 156,000 Allied troops landing on the beaches of Normandy.", "explanation": "Codenamed Operation Overlord, the invasion opened a second front in Western Europe against Nazi Germany. Five beaches — Utah, Omaha, Gold, Juno, and Sword — were assaulted simultaneously.", "quizQuestion": "How many Allied troops landed on D-Day?", "correctAnswer": "Over 156,000", "distractors": ["About 50,000", "Around 300,000", "Roughly 75,000", "About 250,000"], "variants": [{"question": "What was the codename for the D-Day invasion?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Operation Overlord", "distractors": ["Operation Barbarossa", "Operation Market Garden", "Operation Torch"]}, {"question": "How many beaches were assaulted on D-Day?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Five", "distractors": ["Three", "Seven", "Two"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 2, "funScore": 9, "ageRating": "teen", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art panorama of a stormy beach with landing craft opening their ramps, soldiers wading through surf toward fortified bluffs, planes and barrage balloons overhead.", "tags": ["history", "wwii", "famous-battles", "normandy", "military"]}
{"id": "hist-cleopatra-rome-160", "type": "fact", "statement": "Cleopatra VII was the last active ruler of Ptolemaic Egypt, and her death in 30 BCE marked the end of the Hellenistic period.", "explanation": "Cleopatra was a polyglot who spoke nine languages. She formed political and romantic alliances with Julius Caesar and Mark Antony, making Egypt a powerful player in Roman politics before Octavian's conquest.", "quizQuestion": "How many languages did Cleopatra reportedly speak?", "correctAnswer": "Nine", "distractors": ["Three", "Five", "Twelve", "Seven"], "variants": [{"question": "In what year did Cleopatra die?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "30 BCE", "distractors": ["44 BCE", "69 BCE", "14 CE"]}, {"question": "Whose conquest of Egypt ended the Ptolemaic dynasty?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Octavian (Augustus)", "distractors": ["Julius Caesar", "Pompey", "Nero"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 3, "funScore": 8, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art Egyptian palace throne room with a regal queen wearing a golden headdress and cobra crown, surrounded by scrolls, with the Nile visible through columned windows.", "tags": ["history", "classical-antiquity", "ancient-egypt", "women-in-history"]}
{"id": "hist-wright-brothers-161", "type": "fact", "statement": "Orville and Wilbur Wright achieved the first sustained, controlled, powered heavier-than-air flight on December 17, 1903 at Kitty Hawk.", "explanation": "The Wright Flyer traveled 37 meters in 12 seconds on its first flight. By the fourth flight that day, Wilbur flew 260 meters in 59 seconds. Their success came from systematic wind tunnel testing and a novel wing-warping control system.", "quizQuestion": "Where did the Wright brothers make their first powered flight?", "correctAnswer": "Kitty Hawk, North Carolina", "distractors": ["Dayton, Ohio", "Cape Canaveral, Florida", "Chicago, Illinois", "Cape Cod, Massachusetts"], "variants": [{"question": "How far did the Wright Flyer travel on its first flight?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "37 meters", "distractors": ["100 meters", "5 meters", "500 meters"]}, {"question": "What control innovation did the Wright brothers develop?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Wing warping", "distractors": ["Ailerons", "Jet propulsion", "Helicopter rotors"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 2, "funScore": 8, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art biplane with fabric wings lifting off a sandy beach, two men in caps watching, with sand dunes and wind-whipped grass in the background.", "tags": ["history", "inventions", "aviation", "modern"]}
{"id": "hist-renaissance-florence-162", "type": "fact", "statement": "The Renaissance began in Florence, Italy, in the 14th century, driven by wealthy patrons like the Medici family.", "explanation": "Meaning 'rebirth,' the Renaissance saw a revival of classical learning, humanism, and artistic innovation. Florence became the cradle of art, science, and philosophy, producing masters like Leonardo, Michelangelo, and Botticelli.", "quizQuestion": "Which powerful family were the primary patrons of the Florentine Renaissance?", "correctAnswer": "The Medici", "distractors": ["The Borgia", "The Sforza", "The Habsburgs", "The Valois"], "variants": [{"question": "In which century did the Renaissance begin?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "14th century", "distractors": ["12th century", "16th century", "10th century"]}, {"question": "What does 'Renaissance' literally mean?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Rebirth", "distractors": ["Enlightenment", "Revolution", "Discovery"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 2, "funScore": 7, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art Florentine piazza with the iconic Duomo dome in the background, artists painting on easels, scholars debating near a fountain, and Medici banners hanging from buildings.", "tags": ["history", "renaissance", "italy", "art-architecture", "culture"]}
{"id": "hist-code-of-hammurabi-163", "type": "fact", "statement": "The Code of Hammurabi, created around 1754 BCE in Babylon, is one of the earliest known written legal codes.", "explanation": "Inscribed on a 2.25-meter basalt stele, the code contains 282 laws covering commerce, property, family, and criminal justice. It established the principle of 'an eye for an eye' and presumption of innocence.", "quizQuestion": "How many laws does the Code of Hammurabi contain?", "correctAnswer": "282", "distractors": ["100", "500", "42", "150"], "variants": [{"question": "On what material was the Code of Hammurabi inscribed?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "A basalt stele", "distractors": ["Papyrus scrolls", "Clay tablets", "Bronze plates"]}, {"question": "In which ancient city was the Code of Hammurabi created?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Babylon", "distractors": ["Ur", "Memphis", "Athens"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 3, "funScore": 7, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art tall dark stone pillar carved with rows of cuneiform text, standing in a grand Babylonian hall with winged bull statues and torch-lit walls.", "tags": ["history", "ancient-civilizations", "mesopotamia", "law", "ancient-technology"]}
{"id": "hist-mlk-dream-speech-164", "type": "fact", "statement": "Martin Luther King Jr. delivered his 'I Have a Dream' speech on August 28, 1963, during the March on Washington.", "explanation": "Delivered to over 250,000 people at the Lincoln Memorial, the speech became an iconic moment in the American civil rights movement. King called for an end to racism and envisioned a future of equality.", "quizQuestion": "At which landmark was the 'I Have a Dream' speech delivered?", "correctAnswer": "The Lincoln Memorial", "distractors": ["The Capitol Building", "The White House", "Independence Hall", "The Washington Monument"], "variants": [{"question": "How many people attended the March on Washington in 1963?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Over 250,000", "distractors": ["About 50,000", "Roughly 1 million", "Around 10,000"]}, {"question": "In what year did Martin Luther King Jr. deliver the 'I Have a Dream' speech?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "1963", "distractors": ["1955", "1968", "1971"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 1, "funScore": 9, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art scene of a vast crowd stretching along the National Mall reflecting pool, a speaker at a podium before the columned Lincoln Memorial.", "tags": ["history", "civil-rights", "speeches", "united-states", "modern"]}
{"id": "hist-voyager-golden-record-165", "type": "fact", "statement": "NASA's Voyager 1 and 2 spacecraft, launched in 1977, each carry a Golden Record with sounds and images representing life on Earth.", "explanation": "Curated by a committee chaired by Carl Sagan, the records include music from Bach to Chuck Berry, greetings in 55 languages, and 116 images. Voyager 1 entered interstellar space in 2012.", "quizQuestion": "Who chaired the committee that curated the Voyager Golden Records?", "correctAnswer": "Carl Sagan", "distractors": ["Neil deGrasse Tyson", "Stephen Hawking", "Richard Feynman", "Werner von Braun"], "variants": [{"question": "In what year were the Voyager spacecraft launched?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "1977", "distractors": ["1969", "1981", "1972"]}, {"question": "How many languages are represented in the Golden Record greetings?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "55", "distractors": ["20", "100", "35"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 3, "funScore": 10, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art spacecraft with a large dish antenna sailing through a starfield, a gleaming golden disc mounted on its side, with Jupiter and Saturn in the background.", "tags": ["history", "space-race", "nasa", "exploration", "modern"]}
{"id": "hist-battle-thermopylae-166", "type": "fact", "statement": "At the Battle of Thermopylae in 480 BCE, King Leonidas and 300 Spartans led a small Greek force against the massive Persian army of Xerxes I.", "explanation": "The Greeks held the narrow coastal pass for three days before being outflanked via a mountain path. Though a military defeat, the stand inspired Greek unity and contributed to eventual Persian defeat at Salamis and Plataea.", "quizQuestion": "Which Spartan king led the defense at Thermopylae?", "correctAnswer": "Leonidas", "distractors": ["Agis", "Cleomenes", "Pausanias", "Agamemnon"], "variants": [{"question": "How many days did the Greeks hold the pass at Thermopylae?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Three days", "distractors": ["One day", "Seven days", "Two weeks"]}, {"question": "Which Persian king led the invasion at Thermopylae?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Xerxes I", "distractors": ["Darius I", "Cyrus the Great", "Artaxerxes"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 2, "funScore": 9, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art narrow mountain pass between cliffs and sea, a small phalanx of bronze-armored Spartans with red cloaks and round shields facing an enormous advancing army.", "tags": ["history", "classical-antiquity", "famous-battles", "greece", "military"]}
{"id": "hist-roman-aqueducts-167", "type": "fact", "statement": "The ancient Romans built over 400 aqueducts across their empire, with the city of Rome alone supplied by 11 major aqueducts totaling 500+ km.", "explanation": "Using precise engineering with a gradient of just 1:4800, Roman aqueducts delivered 1 million cubic meters of water daily to Rome. Some, like the Pont du Gard in France, still stand 2,000 years later.", "quizQuestion": "Approximately how many major aqueducts supplied the city of Rome?", "correctAnswer": "11", "distractors": ["3", "25", "50", "5"], "variants": [{"question": "How much water did Rome's aqueducts deliver daily?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "About 1 million cubic meters", "distractors": ["10,000 liters", "100,000 cubic meters", "50 million liters"]}, {"question": "Which famous Roman aqueduct still stands in southern France?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Pont du Gard", "distractors": ["Colosseum", "Pantheon", "Appian Way"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 3, "funScore": 7, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art multi-tiered stone aqueduct spanning a lush green valley with a river below, water flowing through the channel on top, Roman countryside stretching behind.", "tags": ["history", "ancient-rome", "ancient-technology", "engineering", "classical-antiquity"]}
{"id": "hist-mata-hari-168", "type": "fact", "statement": "Mata Hari, born Margaretha Zelle, was a Dutch exotic dancer executed by France in 1917 for espionage during World War I.", "explanation": "Though convicted of spying for Germany, historical evidence suggests she was at most a low-level double agent and likely a scapegoat. Her name became synonymous with seductive espionage, though the case remains controversial.", "quizQuestion": "What was Mata Hari's real name?", "correctAnswer": "Margaretha Zelle", "distractors": ["Marie Curie", "Edith Cavell", "Josephine Baker", "Christine Granville"], "variants": [{"question": "For which country was Mata Hari accused of spying?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Germany", "distractors": ["Russia", "Britain", "Austria-Hungary"]}, {"question": "In what year was Mata Hari executed?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "1917", "distractors": ["1914", "1919", "1916"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 4, "funScore": 8, "ageRating": "teen", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art 1910s Parisian scene with a glamorous woman in an elaborate costume on a theater stage, shadowy military figures watching from the wings, spotlight beams crossing.", "tags": ["history", "espionage", "wwi", "women-in-history", "france"]}
{"id": "hist-library-alexandria-169", "type": "fact", "statement": "The Library of Alexandria in Egypt was the largest library of the ancient world, estimated to have held up to 400,000 scrolls at its peak.", "explanation": "Founded in the 3rd century BCE under Ptolemy II, it was a center of scholarship attracting scholars like Euclid, Archimedes, and Eratosthenes. Its gradual decline occurred over centuries, not in a single dramatic fire as popularly believed.", "quizQuestion": "Approximately how many scrolls did the Library of Alexandria hold at its peak?", "correctAnswer": "Up to 400,000", "distractors": ["About 10,000", "Over 2 million", "Roughly 50,000", "About 100,000"], "variants": [{"question": "Under which ruler was the Library of Alexandria founded?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Ptolemy II", "distractors": ["Alexander the Great", "Cleopatra", "Ramesses II"]}, {"question": "Which famous mathematician worked at the Library of Alexandria?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Euclid", "distractors": ["Pythagoras", "Plato", "Confucius"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 3, "funScore": 9, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art grand columned hall filled with floor-to-ceiling shelving of papyrus scrolls, scholars in robes reading and debating, Mediterranean light streaming through high windows.", "tags": ["history", "ancient-civilizations", "ancient-egypt", "scholarship", "archaeology"]}
{"id": "hist-cuban-missile-crisis-170", "type": "fact", "statement": "The Cuban Missile Crisis of October 1962 brought the United States and Soviet Union to the brink of nuclear war for 13 days.", "explanation": "The crisis began when US reconnaissance discovered Soviet nuclear missiles being installed in Cuba. President Kennedy imposed a naval blockade. Soviet Premier Khrushchev ultimately agreed to remove the missiles in exchange for a US pledge not to invade Cuba.", "quizQuestion": "How many days did the Cuban Missile Crisis last?", "correctAnswer": "13 days", "distractors": ["7 days", "30 days", "3 days", "30 days"], "variants": [{"question": "What did the US impose around Cuba during the crisis?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "A naval blockade", "distractors": ["An air strike", "Economic sanctions", "A ground invasion"]}, {"question": "Who was the US president during the Cuban Missile Crisis?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "John F. Kennedy", "distractors": ["Dwight Eisenhower", "Lyndon Johnson", "Richard Nixon"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 2, "funScore": 9, "ageRating": "teen", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art tense war room with military advisors around a table covered in maps and aerial photographs, a large screen showing Cuba with missile site markers.", "tags": ["history", "cold-war", "nuclear", "united-states", "soviet-union"]}
{"id": "hist-vasco-da-gama-171", "type": "fact", "statement": "Vasco da Gama became the first European to reach India by sea in 1498, sailing around the Cape of Good Hope.", "explanation": "His voyage established a direct maritime trade route between Europe and Asia, breaking the Venetian and Arab monopoly on the spice trade. It launched the Portuguese Empire as a global maritime power.", "quizQuestion": "In what year did Vasco da Gama reach India by sea?", "correctAnswer": "1498", "distractors": ["1492", "1519", "1453", "1510"], "variants": [{"question": "Which cape did Vasco da Gama sail around to reach India?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "The Cape of Good Hope", "distractors": ["Cape Horn", "Cape Cod", "Cape Verde"]}, {"question": "What trade monopoly did da Gama's voyage break?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "The Venetian and Arab spice trade monopoly", "distractors": ["The British tea monopoly", "The Dutch fur trade", "The Spanish gold monopoly"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 2, "funScore": 7, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art Portuguese caravel with red crosses on its sails rounding a dramatic rocky cape, stormy seas crashing against the hull, the Indian coast visible on the distant horizon.", "tags": ["history", "age-of-exploration", "portugal", "trade", "silk-road"]}
{"id": "hist-joan-of-arc-172", "type": "fact", "statement": "Joan of Arc, a 17-year-old French peasant girl, led the French army to a pivotal victory at Orléans in 1429 during the Hundred Years' War.", "explanation": "Claiming divine guidance, Joan convinced the Dauphin Charles VII to let her lead troops. Her victory at Orléans turned the tide of the war. Captured by the Burgundians, she was sold to the English and burned at the stake in 1431.", "quizQuestion": "At which battle did Joan of Arc achieve her most famous victory?", "correctAnswer": "The Siege of Orléans", "distractors": ["The Battle of Agincourt", "The Battle of Crécy", "The Battle of Poitiers", "The Battle of Castillon"], "variants": [{"question": "How old was Joan of Arc when she led the French army?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "17", "distractors": ["12", "25", "30"]}, {"question": "In what year was Joan of Arc executed?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "1431", "distractors": ["1429", "1453", "1415"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 2, "funScore": 9, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art young woman in silver armor on horseback carrying a white banner, leading armored knights toward a walled city with the French fleur-de-lis flying overhead.", "tags": ["history", "medieval", "famous-battles", "women-in-history", "france"]}
{"id": "hist-penicillin-discovery-173", "type": "fact", "statement": "Alexander Fleming discovered penicillin in 1928 when he noticed mold killing bacteria in a petri dish he had accidentally left uncovered.", "explanation": "Fleming observed that Penicillium notatum mold produced a substance lethal to Staphylococcus bacteria. Howard Florey and Ernst Boris Chain later developed it into a usable drug, saving millions of lives in WWII and beyond.", "quizQuestion": "What did Alexander Fleming accidentally discover in 1928?", "correctAnswer": "Penicillin", "distractors": ["Aspirin", "Insulin", "Morphine", "Quinine"], "variants": [{"question": "What type of mold produced penicillin?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Penicillium notatum", "distractors": ["Aspergillus niger", "Saccharomyces cerevisiae", "Rhizopus stolonifer"]}, {"question": "Who developed penicillin into a usable drug after Fleming's discovery?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Howard Florey and Ernst Boris Chain", "distractors": ["Louis Pasteur and Robert Koch", "Jonas Salk and Albert Sabin", "Joseph Lister and Ignaz Semmelweis"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 2, "funScore": 8, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art laboratory bench with petri dishes, one showing a clear ring around a blob of blue-green mold where bacteria have been killed, a surprised scientist peering through a microscope.", "tags": ["history", "inventions", "scientific-revolutions", "medicine", "modern"]}
{"id": "hist-dead-sea-scrolls-174", "type": "fact", "statement": "The Dead Sea Scrolls, discovered between 1947 and 1956 in caves near Qumran, are the oldest known manuscripts of the Hebrew Bible.", "explanation": "A Bedouin shepherd stumbled upon the first scrolls in a cave. The collection includes over 900 texts dating from the 3rd century BCE to the 1st century CE, revolutionizing understanding of ancient Judaism and early Christianity.", "quizQuestion": "Where were the Dead Sea Scrolls discovered?", "correctAnswer": "Caves near Qumran", "distractors": ["The Valley of the Kings", "Under the Temple Mount", "In the Pyramids of Giza", "In a Roman library"], "variants": [{"question": "Who first discovered the Dead Sea Scrolls?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "A Bedouin shepherd", "distractors": ["A British archaeologist", "A Roman soldier", "A Greek monk"]}, {"question": "How many texts comprise the Dead Sea Scrolls collection?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Over 900", "distractors": ["About 50", "Roughly 5,000", "Exactly 100"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 3, "funScore": 8, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art dark cave with clay jars on rocky shelves, ancient parchment scrolls partially unrolled revealing faded Hebrew text, shafts of desert light entering from above.", "tags": ["history", "archaeology", "ancient-civilizations", "religion", "documents"]}
{"id": "hist-manhattan-project-175", "type": "fact", "statement": "The Manhattan Project (1942–1946) was a secret US-led program that developed the first nuclear weapons, employing over 125,000 people.", "explanation": "Led by J. Robert Oppenheimer, the project conducted the first nuclear test (Trinity) on July 16, 1945, in New Mexico. The resulting bombs were dropped on Hiroshima and Nagasaki in August 1945, ending World War II.", "quizQuestion": "Who was the scientific director of the Manhattan Project?", "correctAnswer": "J. Robert Oppenheimer", "distractors": ["Albert Einstein", "Enrico Fermi", "Niels Bohr", "Werner Heisenberg"], "variants": [{"question": "What was the name of the first nuclear test?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Trinity", "distractors": ["Fat Man", "Little Boy", "Ivy Mike"]}, {"question": "How many people worked on the Manhattan Project?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Over 125,000", "distractors": ["About 5,000", "Around 500", "Nearly 1 million"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 3, "funScore": 8, "ageRating": "teen", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art desert landscape with a distant mushroom cloud rising into the sky, scientists in white coats watching through dark goggles from a concrete bunker.", "tags": ["history", "wwii", "inventions", "nuclear", "united-states"]}
{"id": "hist-viking-north-america-176", "type": "fact", "statement": "Norse Vikings, led by Leif Erikson, reached North America around 1000 CE, nearly 500 years before Christopher Columbus.", "explanation": "Archaeological evidence at L'Anse aux Meadows in Newfoundland, Canada, confirms a Norse settlement. The Vikings called the region Vinland due to the wild grapes they found there.", "quizQuestion": "What did the Vikings call the region of North America they discovered?", "correctAnswer": "Vinland", "distractors": ["Greenland", "Markland", "Helluland", "Thule"], "variants": [{"question": "Where is the confirmed Norse settlement in North America located?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "L'Anse aux Meadows, Newfoundland", "distractors": ["Plymouth Rock, Massachusetts", "Jamestown, Virginia", "St. Augustine, Florida"]}, {"question": "Approximately when did the Vikings reach North America?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Around 1000 CE", "distractors": ["800 CE", "1200 CE", "500 CE"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 3, "funScore": 8, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art Viking longship with a dragon prow beached on a forested North American shore, Norse explorers in furs stepping onto a rocky coast with autumn-colored trees.", "tags": ["history", "age-of-exploration", "vikings", "medieval", "archaeology"]}
{"id": "hist-french-revolution-177", "type": "fact", "statement": "The French Revolution began on July 14, 1789, with the storming of the Bastille, a fortress-prison symbolizing royal tyranny.", "explanation": "Driven by economic hardship, inequality, and Enlightenment ideas, the revolution overthrew the monarchy, established a republic, and introduced the Declaration of the Rights of Man. It profoundly influenced modern democracy worldwide.", "quizQuestion": "What event on July 14, 1789, is considered the start of the French Revolution?", "correctAnswer": "The storming of the Bastille", "distractors": ["The execution of Louis XVI", "The Tennis Court Oath", "The Women's March on Versailles", "The arrest of Napoleon"], "variants": [{"question": "What document did the French Revolution produce declaring human rights?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "The Declaration of the Rights of Man", "distractors": ["The Magna Carta", "The Bill of Rights", "The Geneva Convention"]}, {"question": "July 14 is now celebrated in France as what holiday?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Bastille Day", "distractors": ["Republic Day", "Liberation Day", "Unity Day"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 2, "funScore": 8, "ageRating": "teen", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art fortress with tall stone towers being stormed by a crowd carrying torches, pikes, and revolutionary tricolor flags, smoke rising from cannon fire.", "tags": ["history", "french-revolution", "modern", "civil-rights", "europe"]}
{"id": "hist-treaty-of-westphalia-178", "type": "fact", "statement": "The Peace of Westphalia in 1648 ended the Thirty Years' War and established the modern concept of state sovereignty.", "explanation": "The treaties recognized the principle that each state has sovereignty over its territory and domestic affairs, free from external interference. This laid the foundation for the modern international system of nation-states.", "quizQuestion": "What major concept in international relations did the Peace of Westphalia establish?", "correctAnswer": "State sovereignty", "distractors": ["Freedom of the seas", "Universal human rights", "Free trade zones", "Freedom of navigation"], "variants": [{"question": "Which war did the Peace of Westphalia end?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "The Thirty Years' War", "distractors": ["The Hundred Years' War", "The Seven Years' War", "The War of the Roses"]}, {"question": "In what year was the Peace of Westphalia signed?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "1648", "distractors": ["1618", "1776", "1689"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 4, "funScore": 6, "ageRating": "teen", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art grand hall with diplomats in 17th-century dress signing documents at a long ornate table, candlelight illuminating maps and wax seals on parchments.", "tags": ["history", "diplomacy", "early-modern", "europe", "treaties"]}
{"id": "hist-moon-landing-179", "type": "fact", "statement": "On July 20, 1969, Neil Armstrong became the first human to walk on the Moon during the Apollo 11 mission.", "explanation": "Armstrong's famous words, 'That's one small step for man, one giant leap for mankind,' were heard by an estimated 600 million television viewers worldwide. Buzz Aldrin joined him on the surface while Michael Collins orbited above.", "quizQuestion": "Who was the second person to walk on the Moon during Apollo 11?", "correctAnswer": "Buzz Aldrin", "distractors": ["Michael Collins", "John Glenn", "Pete Conrad", "Apollo 9"], "variants": [{"question": "How many people watched the Moon landing on television?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "About 600 million", "distractors": ["10 million", "1 billion", "100 million"]}, {"question": "What Apollo mission achieved the first Moon landing?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Apollo 11", "distractors": ["Apollo 13", "Apollo 8", "Apollo 7"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 1, "funScore": 10, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art astronaut in a white spacesuit planting a flag on the gray lunar surface, boot prints in the dust, Earth visible as a blue marble in the black sky above.", "tags": ["history", "space-race", "united-states", "exploration", "modern"]}
{"id": "hist-samurai-bushido-180", "type": "fact", "statement": "Bushido, the 'way of the warrior,' was the unwritten code of conduct followed by Japanese samurai emphasizing honor, loyalty, and self-discipline.", "explanation": "Formalized during the Edo period (1603–1868), Bushido drew from Zen Buddhism, Confucianism, and Shintoism. It demanded martial arts mastery, frugality, and willingness to die rather than suffer dishonor.", "quizQuestion": "What does 'Bushido' literally translate to?", "correctAnswer": "Way of the warrior", "distractors": ["Path of the sword", "Honor of the clan", "Spirit of battle", "Code of the sword"], "variants": [{"question": "During which period was Bushido formalized?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "The Edo period", "distractors": ["The Heian period", "The Meiji era", "The Kamakura period"]}, {"question": "Which religion influenced Bushido's emphasis on meditation and self-control?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Zen Buddhism", "distractors": ["Hinduism", "Taoism", "Christianity"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 3, "funScore": 8, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art samurai in traditional armor kneeling in a serene Zen garden with cherry blossoms falling, a katana placed carefully before him on a wooden stand.", "tags": ["history", "japan", "medieval", "culture", "military"]}
{"id": "hist-great-wall-china-181", "type": "fact", "statement": "The Great Wall of China stretches over 21,000 km and was built over 2,000 years by multiple dynasties starting from the 7th century BCE.", "explanation": "Contrary to popular belief, the Wall is not visible from space with the naked eye. Most of the existing wall was built during the Ming Dynasty (1368–1644). It served as defense, border control, and a trade regulation tool.", "quizQuestion": "Which dynasty built most of the existing Great Wall?", "correctAnswer": "The Ming Dynasty", "distractors": ["The Han Dynasty", "The Qin Dynasty", "The Tang Dynasty", "The Qin Dynasty"], "variants": [{"question": "How long is the Great Wall of China?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Over 21,000 km", "distractors": ["About 5,000 km", "Roughly 50,000 km", "Around 1,000 km"]}, {"question": "Is the Great Wall visible from space with the naked eye?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "No, this is a common myth", "distractors": ["Yes, it is clearly visible", "Only from low orbit", "Only with binoculars"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 2, "funScore": 7, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art winding stone wall with watchtowers snaking along mountain ridges, green forested valleys below, and misty peaks fading into the distance.", "tags": ["history", "ancient-civilizations", "ancient-technology", "china", "engineering"]}
{"id": "hist-battle-of-stalingrad-182", "type": "fact", "statement": "The Battle of Stalingrad (1942–1943) was the bloodiest battle in human history, with nearly 2 million total casualties.", "explanation": "The Soviet defense and counterattack at Stalingrad destroyed the German 6th Army and marked the turning point of WWII on the Eastern Front. Street-by-street urban combat in freezing conditions made it devastatingly brutal.", "quizQuestion": "Approximately how many total casualties occurred at the Battle of Stalingrad?", "correctAnswer": "Nearly 2 million", "distractors": ["About 500,000", "Roughly 5 million", "Around 200,000", "About 100,000"], "variants": [{"question": "Which German army was destroyed at Stalingrad?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "The 6th Army", "distractors": ["The 3rd Army", "The 1st Panzer Army", "The Afrika Korps"]}, {"question": "What did the Battle of Stalingrad mark on the Eastern Front?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "The turning point of the war", "distractors": ["The start of the war", "A minor skirmish", "A German victory"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 3, "funScore": 7, "ageRating": "teen", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art ruined cityscape with crumbling buildings, soldiers fighting among rubble and snow, tanks partially buried in debris, dark smoke-filled skies overhead.", "tags": ["history", "wwii", "famous-battles", "soviet-union", "military"]}
{"id": "hist-ancient-olympics-183", "type": "fact", "statement": "The ancient Olympic Games were held every four years in Olympia, Greece, from 776 BCE to 393 CE — a span of nearly 1,200 years.", "explanation": "Originally a religious festival honoring Zeus, the games featured events like chariot racing, wrestling, and the stadion foot race. A sacred truce halted wars during the games, and victors received olive wreaths.", "quizQuestion": "For how many years were the ancient Olympic Games held?", "correctAnswer": "Nearly 1,200 years", "distractors": ["About 500 years", "Roughly 200 years", "Over 2,000 years", "About 300 years"], "variants": [{"question": "Which god were the ancient Olympics held in honor of?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Zeus", "distractors": ["Apollo", "Athena", "Poseidon"]}, {"question": "What prize did ancient Olympic victors receive?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "An olive wreath", "distractors": ["A gold medal", "A silver cup", "A laurel crown"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 2, "funScore": 7, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art ancient Greek stadium with stone seating tiers, athletes in tunics competing in a foot race on a sandy track, a grand temple of Zeus visible on a nearby hill.", "tags": ["history", "classical-antiquity", "greece", "sports", "culture"]}
{"id": "hist-enigma-machine-design-184", "type": "fact", "statement": "The Enigma machine used by Nazi Germany had 158,962,555,217,826,360,000 possible settings, making it seem unbreakable.", "explanation": "The machine used rotating cipher discs (rotors) and a plugboard to encrypt messages. Its apparent security lay in the astronomically large number of configurations, but repeated patterns and operator errors gave codebreakers crucial footholds.", "quizQuestion": "What components of the Enigma machine created its encryption?", "correctAnswer": "Rotating cipher discs (rotors) and a plugboard", "distractors": ["A single rotating wheel", "Magnetic tape strips", "Punched paper cards", "A single cipher wheel"], "variants": [{"question": "What weakness helped codebreakers crack Enigma?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Repeated patterns and operator errors", "distractors": ["A design flaw in the rotors", "A stolen master key", "Bribery of German engineers"]}, {"question": "How many possible settings did the Enigma machine have?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Over 158 quintillion", "distractors": ["About 1 million", "Roughly 1 billion", "Exactly 26 factorial"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 5, "funScore": 9, "ageRating": "teen", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art dark wooden box with a typewriter keyboard, rows of letter lights, and three visible rotating discs, wires running to a plugboard below, in a dim radio room.", "tags": ["history", "espionage", "wwii", "codebreaking", "ancient-technology"]}
{"id": "hist-hypatia-alexandria-185", "type": "fact", "statement": "Hypatia of Alexandria (c. 360–415 CE) was one of the first known female mathematicians and astronomers, and head of the Neoplatonic school.", "explanation": "Hypatia taught philosophy, mathematics, and astronomy in Alexandria. She invented an improved astrolabe and a hydrometer. She was murdered by a Christian mob during a period of religious and political turmoil.", "quizQuestion": "What scientific instrument did Hypatia of Alexandria help improve?", "correctAnswer": "The astrolabe", "distractors": ["The telescope", "The compass", "The sundial", "The sextant"], "variants": [{"question": "What school did Hypatia head in Alexandria?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "The Neoplatonic school", "distractors": ["The Lyceum", "The Academy", "The Mouseion"]}, {"question": "In what century did Hypatia live?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "4th–5th century CE", "distractors": ["1st century BCE", "7th century CE", "2nd century CE"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 4, "funScore": 8, "ageRating": "teen", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art woman in classical robes lecturing to students in a columned hall, astronomical charts and geometric diagrams on tablets around her, a brass astrolabe in her hand.", "tags": ["history", "women-in-history", "scientific-revolutions", "classical-antiquity", "astronomy"]}
{"id": "hist-tenochtitlan-190", "type": "fact", "statement": "Tenochtitlan, the Aztec capital built on an island in Lake Texcoco, had a population of over 200,000 when the Spanish arrived in 1519.", "explanation": "Larger than most European cities of its time, Tenochtitlan featured aqueducts, causeways, floating gardens (chinampas), and grand pyramids. Hernán Cortés and his forces destroyed it in 1521, building Mexico City on its ruins.", "quizQuestion": "What innovative farming technique did the Aztecs use in Tenochtitlan?", "correctAnswer": "Chinampas (floating gardens)", "distractors": ["Terrace farming", "Crop rotation", "Slash-and-burn agriculture", "Irrigation canals"], "variants": [{"question": "What was the population of Tenochtitlan when the Spanish arrived?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Over 200,000", "distractors": ["About 50,000", "Roughly 1 million", "Around 10,000"]}, {"question": "What modern city was built on the ruins of Tenochtitlan?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Mexico City", "distractors": ["Guadalajara", "Havana", "Lima"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 3, "funScore": 8, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art island city on a shimmering lake with pyramid temples rising above causeways, canoes paddling between floating garden plots, snow-capped volcanoes in the background.", "tags": ["history", "ancient-civilizations", "aztec", "age-of-exploration", "archaeology"]}
{"id": "hist-harriet-tubman-186", "type": "fact", "statement": "Harriet Tubman escaped slavery in 1849 and made approximately 13 rescue missions via the Underground Railroad, freeing around 70 enslaved people.", "explanation": "Tubman used a network of safe houses known as the Underground Railroad. During the Civil War, she served as a scout, spy, and nurse for the Union Army, and became the first woman to lead an armed raid (at Combahee Ferry).", "quizQuestion": "Approximately how many enslaved people did Harriet Tubman free via the Underground Railroad?", "correctAnswer": "Around 70", "distractors": ["Over 300", "About 10", "Roughly 1,000", "About 500"], "variants": [{"question": "In what year did Harriet Tubman escape slavery?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "1849", "distractors": ["1861", "1835", "1820"]}, {"question": "What role did Tubman serve during the Civil War?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Scout, spy, and nurse for the Union Army", "distractors": ["Confederate diplomat", "Journalist", "Plantation owner"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 2, "funScore": 9, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art nighttime forest scene with a determined woman leading a small group along a hidden path, the North Star visible through tree canopy, a distant lantern at a safe house.", "tags": ["history", "civil-rights", "women-in-history", "united-states", "espionage"]}
{"id": "hist-justinian-plague-187", "type": "fact", "statement": "The Plague of Justinian (541–549 CE) killed an estimated 25–50 million people, roughly half the population of the Byzantine Empire.", "explanation": "Named after Emperor Justinian I, who contracted but survived the disease, it was caused by Yersinia pestis — the same bacterium behind the Black Death. It weakened the Byzantine Empire permanently and may have contributed to the rise of Islam.", "quizQuestion": "Which emperor gave the Plague of Justinian its name?", "correctAnswer": "Justinian I", "distractors": ["Constantine", "Theodosius", "Marcus Aurelius", "Constantine"], "variants": [{"question": "What bacterium caused the Plague of Justinian?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Yersinia pestis", "distractors": ["Mycobacterium leprae", "Variola major", "Treponema pallidum"]}, {"question": "Approximately what fraction of the Byzantine population died in the plague?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "About half", "distractors": ["One-tenth", "One-quarter", "Three-quarters"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 4, "funScore": 7, "ageRating": "teen", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art Byzantine city with domed churches and ornate buildings, empty streets with abandoned market stalls, a somber emperor looking out from a palace balcony.", "tags": ["history", "pandemics", "classical-antiquity", "byzantine", "disease"]}
{"id": "hist-spinning-jenny-188", "type": "fact", "statement": "James Hargreaves invented the Spinning Jenny around 1764, a multi-spindle spinning frame that dramatically increased yarn production.", "explanation": "The Spinning Jenny allowed one worker to operate eight spindles at once, later expanded to 120. It was a key catalyst of the Industrial Revolution's textile boom and one of the first machines to automate manual labor.", "quizQuestion": "What did the Spinning Jenny dramatically increase the production of?", "correctAnswer": "Yarn", "distractors": ["Steel", "Paper", "Flour", "Cloth"], "variants": [{"question": "Who invented the Spinning Jenny?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "James Hargreaves", "distractors": ["Eli Whitney", "Richard Arkwright", "Edmund Cartwright"]}, {"question": "How many spindles could the original Spinning Jenny operate?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Eight", "distractors": ["Two", "Twenty", "One hundred"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 3, "funScore": 6, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art wooden spinning machine with multiple spindles whirring in a cottage workshop, threads of yarn extending to bobbins, a worker in period clothing operating it.", "tags": ["history", "industrial-revolution", "inventions", "textiles", "britain"]}
{"id": "hist-battle-of-hastings-189", "type": "fact", "statement": "The Battle of Hastings on October 14, 1066, saw William the Conqueror defeat King Harold II, ending Anglo-Saxon rule in England.", "explanation": "William, Duke of Normandy, claimed the English throne and invaded with about 7,000 troops. Harold was killed (possibly by an arrow to the eye), and the Norman Conquest fundamentally changed English language, law, and culture.", "quizQuestion": "Who won the Battle of Hastings in 1066?", "correctAnswer": "William the Conqueror", "distractors": ["King Harold II", "King Cnut", "Alfred the Great", "King Cnut"], "variants": [{"question": "How is King Harold II traditionally said to have died at Hastings?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "An arrow to the eye", "distractors": ["A sword wound", "Drowning", "Falling from his horse"]}, {"question": "What type of rule ended in England after the Battle of Hastings?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Anglo-Saxon", "distractors": ["Viking", "Roman", "Celtic"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 2, "funScore": 8, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art hilltop battlefield with Norman knights on horseback charging uphill against a shield wall of Anglo-Saxon infantry, arrows arcing through the sky, the Bayeux Tapestry style.", "tags": ["history", "medieval", "famous-battles", "england", "military"]}
{"id": "hist-cambridge-five-191", "type": "fact", "statement": "The Cambridge Five were British double agents recruited by Soviet intelligence at Cambridge University in the 1930s who passed secrets for decades.", "explanation": "The group — Kim Philby, Donald Maclean, Guy Burgess, Anthony Blunt, and John Cairncross — infiltrated MI5, MI6, and the Foreign Office. Their betrayal compromised Western intelligence operations throughout the Cold War.", "quizQuestion": "How many members made up the Cambridge spy ring?", "correctAnswer": "Five", "distractors": ["Three", "Seven", "Two", "Ten"], "variants": [{"question": "Which member of the Cambridge Five rose highest in MI6?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Kim Philby", "distractors": ["Donald Maclean", "Anthony Blunt", "Guy Burgess"]}, {"question": "For which country did the Cambridge Five spy?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "The Soviet Union", "distractors": ["Nazi Germany", "China", "France"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 4, "funScore": 8, "ageRating": "teen", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art 1930s Cambridge college courtyard with Gothic spires, well-dressed young men exchanging covert documents beneath lamplight, shadows on ancient stone walls.", "tags": ["history", "espionage", "cold-war", "britain", "modern"]}
{"id": "hist-indus-valley-civilization-192", "type": "fact", "statement": "The Indus Valley Civilization (3300–1300 BCE) had advanced urban planning with grid-pattern streets, indoor plumbing, and sophisticated sewage systems.", "explanation": "Cities like Mohenjo-daro and Harappa housed up to 40,000 people each. They had standardized weights and measures, granaries, and public baths. Their undeciphered script remains one of archaeology's great mysteries.", "quizQuestion": "Which ancient civilization had indoor plumbing and sewage systems around 2500 BCE?", "correctAnswer": "The Indus Valley Civilization", "distractors": ["Ancient Egypt", "Ancient Greece", "Ancient Rome", "Ancient Mesopotamia"], "variants": [{"question": "Name one major city of the Indus Valley Civilization.", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Mohenjo-daro", "distractors": ["Babylon", "Memphis", "Persepolis"]}, {"question": "What about the Indus Valley script remains a mystery?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "It has never been deciphered", "distractors": ["It was destroyed", "It was in Sanskrit", "It used pictographs only"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 3, "funScore": 8, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art bird's-eye view of a planned ancient city with grid streets, multi-story brick buildings, a large central bath, and covered drainage channels running along the roads.", "tags": ["history", "ancient-civilizations", "ancient-technology", "archaeology", "india"]}
{"id": "hist-ada-lovelace-193", "type": "fact", "statement": "Ada Lovelace wrote the first published computer algorithm in 1843, designed for Charles Babbage's Analytical Engine.", "explanation": "The daughter of poet Lord Byron, Ada Lovelace saw potential in Babbage's machine beyond mere calculation. Her notes on the Analytical Engine included what is recognized as the first algorithm intended for machine processing, making her a computing pioneer.", "quizQuestion": "What machine was Ada Lovelace's algorithm designed for?", "correctAnswer": "Babbage's Analytical Engine", "distractors": ["The ENIAC", "The Difference Engine", "Turing's Bombe", "The Jacquard Loom"], "variants": [{"question": "In what year did Ada Lovelace publish her algorithm?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "1843", "distractors": ["1801", "1890", "1820"]}, {"question": "Who was Ada Lovelace's famous poet father?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Lord Byron", "distractors": ["Percy Shelley", "John Keats", "William Wordsworth"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 3, "funScore": 8, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art Victorian study with a woman in a full dress writing mathematical notations at a desk, beside a large mechanical computing machine of brass gears and levers.", "tags": ["history", "women-in-history", "inventions", "scientific-revolutions", "computing"]}
{"id": "hist-suez-canal-194", "type": "fact", "statement": "The Suez Canal, completed in 1869, reduced the sailing distance between London and Mumbai from 19,800 km to 11,600 km.", "explanation": "Designed by French engineer Ferdinand de Lesseps, the 193-km canal through Egypt connects the Mediterranean and Red Seas. It eliminated the need to sail around Africa and transformed global trade routes.", "quizQuestion": "By how much did the Suez Canal reduce the London-to-Mumbai sailing distance?", "correctAnswer": "From 19,800 km to 11,600 km", "distractors": ["From 30,000 km to 5,000 km", "From 15,000 km to 14,000 km", "From 25,000 km to 20,000 km", "From 10,000 km to 8,000 km"], "variants": [{"question": "Who designed the Suez Canal?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Ferdinand de Lesseps", "distractors": ["Gustave Eiffel", "Isambard Kingdom Brunel", "Thomas Telford"]}, {"question": "Which two seas does the Suez Canal connect?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "The Mediterranean and Red Seas", "distractors": ["The Atlantic and Pacific Oceans", "The Black and Caspian Seas", "The North and Baltic Seas"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 3, "funScore": 7, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art long straight canal cutting through flat desert sand, a large steamship passing through, palm trees lining the banks, Egyptian buildings visible in the distance.", "tags": ["history", "inventions", "engineering", "trade", "modern"]}
{"id": "hist-trail-of-tears-195", "type": "fact", "statement": "The Trail of Tears (1830–1850) was the forced relocation of approximately 60,000 Native Americans from southeastern US to Indian Territory, killing thousands.", "explanation": "Following the Indian Removal Act of 1830, the Cherokee, Creek, Chickasaw, Choctaw, and Seminole nations were forcibly marched westward. An estimated 15,000 Native Americans died from disease, starvation, and exposure during the journey.", "quizQuestion": "What legislation authorized the forced removal of Native Americans in the Trail of Tears?", "correctAnswer": "The Indian Removal Act of 1830", "distractors": ["The Homestead Act", "The Dawes Act", "The Northwest Ordinance", "The Emancipation Proclamation"], "variants": [{"question": "How many Native Americans were forcibly relocated during the Trail of Tears?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Approximately 60,000", "distractors": ["About 5,000", "Roughly 500,000", "Around 1 million"]}, {"question": "To where were Native Americans relocated during the Trail of Tears?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Indian Territory (present-day Oklahoma)", "distractors": ["California", "Canada", "Mexico"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 3, "funScore": 5, "ageRating": "teen", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art somber winter landscape with a long line of Native American families walking westward on a dusty trail, bundled against cold, bare trees, and overcast skies.", "tags": ["history", "civil-rights", "united-states", "native-americans", "modern"]}
{"id": "hist-compass-invention-196", "type": "fact", "statement": "The magnetic compass was invented in China during the Han Dynasty (around 206 BCE–220 CE), originally used for feng shui before navigation.", "explanation": "Early compasses used lodestone (magnetite) shaped into a spoon on a bronze plate. By the Song Dynasty (11th century), compass navigation enabled Chinese maritime exploration. The technology later spread to Europe via Arab traders.", "quizQuestion": "What was the magnetic compass originally used for in China?", "correctAnswer": "Feng shui", "distractors": ["Naval warfare", "Mining", "Astronomy", "Astronomy"], "variants": [{"question": "During which Chinese dynasty was the compass invented?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "The Han Dynasty", "distractors": ["The Ming Dynasty", "The Tang Dynasty", "The Qin Dynasty"]}, {"question": "What natural mineral was used in early Chinese compasses?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Lodestone (magnetite)", "distractors": ["Quartz", "Iron pyrite", "Jade"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 3, "funScore": 7, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art ancient Chinese study with a lodestone spoon balanced on a polished bronze plate, faint directional markings visible, scrolls and an incense burner nearby.", "tags": ["history", "ancient-technology", "inventions", "china", "silk-road"]}
{"id": "hist-battle-of-midway-197", "type": "fact", "statement": "The Battle of Midway (June 1942) was the turning point of the Pacific War, where the US Navy sank four Japanese aircraft carriers.", "explanation": "American codebreakers had decrypted Japanese plans, enabling an ambush. The loss of four fleet carriers — Akagi, Kaga, Soryu, and Hiryu — along with their experienced pilots was a blow from which Japan's navy never recovered.", "quizQuestion": "How many Japanese aircraft carriers were sunk at the Battle of Midway?", "correctAnswer": "Four", "distractors": ["Two", "Six", "One", "Three"], "variants": [{"question": "What intelligence advantage did the US have at Midway?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "They had broken the Japanese naval code", "distractors": ["A captured spy", "Radar superiority", "Submarine reconnaissance"]}, {"question": "In what month and year was the Battle of Midway fought?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "June 1942", "distractors": ["December 1941", "August 1945", "March 1943"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 3, "funScore": 8, "ageRating": "teen", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art aerial view of a Pacific battle with dive bombers plunging toward a burning aircraft carrier, anti-aircraft fire tracers, thick black smoke billowing across blue ocean.", "tags": ["history", "wwii", "famous-battles", "pacific", "military"]}
{"id": "hist-rosa-parks-198", "type": "fact", "statement": "Rosa Parks refused to give up her bus seat to a white passenger on December 1, 1955, in Montgomery, Alabama, sparking the Montgomery Bus Boycott.", "explanation": "Parks, a trained NAACP activist, was arrested for violating segregation laws. The resulting 381-day bus boycott, led by the young Martin Luther King Jr., ended when the Supreme Court ruled bus segregation unconstitutional.", "quizQuestion": "How long did the Montgomery Bus Boycott last?", "correctAnswer": "381 days", "distractors": ["30 days", "One year", "Two weeks", "One week"], "variants": [{"question": "Who led the Montgomery Bus Boycott?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Martin Luther King Jr.", "distractors": ["Malcolm X", "Jesse Jackson", "Thurgood Marshall"]}, {"question": "What Supreme Court ruling ended bus segregation?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Browder v. Gayle (1956)", "distractors": ["Brown v. Board of Education", "Plessy v. Ferguson", "Loving v. Virginia"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 2, "funScore": 8, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art 1950s city bus interior with a dignified woman seated firmly in her seat, other passengers watching, the Montgomery cityscape visible through the bus windows.", "tags": ["history", "civil-rights", "united-states", "women-in-history", "modern"]}
{"id": "hist-printing-movable-type-china-199", "type": "fact", "statement": "Bi Sheng invented the world's first movable type printing system around 1040 CE in Song Dynasty China, nearly 400 years before Gutenberg.", "explanation": "Bi Sheng created individual characters from baked clay that could be rearranged and reused. Though revolutionary, the system was less practical for Chinese with its thousands of characters than Gutenberg's later Latin-alphabet version.", "quizQuestion": "Who invented the first movable type printing system?", "correctAnswer": "Bi Sheng", "distractors": ["Johannes Gutenberg", "Cai Lun", "Zhang Heng", "Zhang Heng"], "variants": [{"question": "What material did Bi Sheng use for his movable type?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Baked clay", "distractors": ["Metal", "Wood", "Stone"]}, {"question": "During which Chinese dynasty did Bi Sheng invent movable type?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "The Song Dynasty", "distractors": ["The Tang Dynasty", "The Han Dynasty", "The Ming Dynasty"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 4, "funScore": 7, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art Song Dynasty workshop with small clay character blocks arranged in wooden frames, a craftsman setting type, printed pages drying on racks, ink pots nearby.", "tags": ["history", "inventions", "ancient-technology", "china", "printing"]}
{"id": "hist-charge-of-light-brigade-200", "type": "fact", "statement": "The Charge of the Light Brigade at the Battle of Balaclava (1854) saw 670 British cavalrymen charge directly into Russian artillery due to a miscommunicated order.", "explanation": "During the Crimean War, a vague order led Lord Cardigan to lead his light cavalry against a heavily fortified Russian gun position. Nearly 300 men were killed or wounded in the disastrous charge, immortalized in Tennyson's poem.", "quizQuestion": "What caused the disastrous Charge of the Light Brigade?", "correctAnswer": "A miscommunicated order", "distractors": ["A deliberate diversionary tactic", "An act of cowardice", "A Russian trap", "A deliberate suicide mission"], "variants": [{"question": "During which war did the Charge of the Light Brigade occur?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "The Crimean War", "distractors": ["The Napoleonic Wars", "World War I", "The Boer War"]}, {"question": "Which poet immortalized the Charge of the Light Brigade?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Alfred, Lord Tennyson", "distractors": ["Rudyard Kipling", "William Wordsworth", "Robert Burns"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 4, "funScore": 8, "ageRating": "teen", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art dramatic cavalry charge with horsemen in blue uniforms galloping toward smoke-belching cannon positions, fallen horses and riders in the foreground, a narrow valley framing the scene.", "tags": ["history", "famous-battles", "military", "britain", "crimean-war"]}
{"id": "hist-alexander-the-great-201", "type": "fact", "statement": "Alexander the Great created one of the largest empires in ancient history by age 30, stretching from Greece to northwestern India.", "explanation": "Tutored by Aristotle, Alexander never lost a battle. His conquests spread Greek culture (Hellenism) across the known world. He founded over 20 cities named Alexandria and died in Babylon in 323 BCE, aged 32.", "quizQuestion": "Who was Alexander the Great's famous tutor?", "correctAnswer": "Aristotle", "distractors": ["Plato", "Socrates", "Euclid", "Homer"], "variants": [{"question": "At what age did Alexander the Great die?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "32", "distractors": ["25", "40", "50"]}, {"question": "How many cities named Alexandria did Alexander found?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Over 20", "distractors": ["One", "Five", "Fifty"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 2, "funScore": 9, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art young king in golden armor on a rearing warhorse, a vast army stretching behind him across dusty plains, conquered cities and mountains on the horizon.", "tags": ["history", "classical-antiquity", "famous-battles", "greece", "military"]}
{"id": "hist-napoleon-exile-202", "type": "fact", "statement": "Napoleon Bonaparte was exiled twice: first to Elba in 1814 (he escaped after 10 months) and then to Saint Helena in 1815, where he died in 1821.", "explanation": "After his defeat and first exile to Elba, Napoleon escaped and returned to France, raising an army for his 'Hundred Days' campaign. After his final defeat at Waterloo, the British exiled him to the remote South Atlantic island of Saint Helena.", "quizQuestion": "From which island did Napoleon famously escape during his first exile?", "correctAnswer": "Elba", "distractors": ["Corsica", "Saint Helena", "Sicily", "Corsica"], "variants": [{"question": "How long did Napoleon's first exile on Elba last?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "About 10 months", "distractors": ["5 years", "3 weeks", "2 years"]}, {"question": "On which island did Napoleon die?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Saint Helena", "distractors": ["Elba", "Corsica", "Malta"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 3, "funScore": 8, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art rocky island with a lone figure in a bicorne hat standing on a cliff edge overlooking a vast ocean, a small guard house and British flag behind him.", "tags": ["history", "famous-battles", "france", "military", "modern"]}
{"id": "hist-emancipation-proclamation-203", "type": "fact", "statement": "Abraham Lincoln's Emancipation Proclamation, issued January 1, 1863, declared enslaved people in Confederate states 'forever free.'", "explanation": "While it did not immediately free anyone (it applied only to rebelling states), it transformed the Civil War into a fight against slavery and allowed African Americans to serve in the Union Army. About 180,000 Black soldiers eventually served.", "quizQuestion": "In what year was the Emancipation Proclamation issued?", "correctAnswer": "1863", "distractors": ["1865", "1861", "1850", "1870"], "variants": [{"question": "To which states did the Emancipation Proclamation apply?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Confederate (rebelling) states", "distractors": ["All US states", "Northern states only", "Border states"]}, {"question": "How many Black soldiers served in the Union Army after the Proclamation?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "About 180,000", "distractors": ["About 10,000", "Over 1 million", "Roughly 50,000"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 2, "funScore": 7, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art scene of a tall bearded president signing a document at a desk in a lamp-lit office, an American flag draped behind, chains breaking symbolically in the foreground.", "tags": ["history", "civil-rights", "united-states", "documents", "modern"]}
{"id": "hist-easter-island-moai-204", "type": "fact", "statement": "The Moai statues of Easter Island (Rapa Nui) number nearly 900, carved between 1250 and 1500 CE from volcanic tuff.", "explanation": "The Rapa Nui people carved these monolithic statues, averaging 4 meters tall and 12 tonnes, to honor ancestral chiefs. Researchers discovered they were 'walked' to their platforms using rocking motions and ropes — not rolled on logs as once believed.", "quizQuestion": "How were the Moai statues most likely transported to their platforms?", "correctAnswer": "'Walked' using rocking motions and ropes", "distractors": ["Rolled on logs", "Dragged on sleds", "Floated on rafts", "Carried by elephants"], "variants": [{"question": "How many Moai statues exist on Easter Island?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Nearly 900", "distractors": ["About 100", "Over 5,000", "Exactly 50"]}, {"question": "What material are the Moai statues carved from?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Volcanic tuff", "distractors": ["Granite", "Marble", "Limestone"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 3, "funScore": 9, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art row of massive stone heads with elongated features on a grassy coastal hillside, ocean waves crashing below, a dramatic sunset casting long shadows behind the statues.", "tags": ["history", "archaeology", "ancient-technology", "polynesia", "mysteries"]}
{"id": "hist-florence-nightingale-205", "type": "fact", "statement": "Florence Nightingale used statistical graphics to convince the British government that poor sanitation, not battle wounds, was the main killer of soldiers in the Crimean War.", "explanation": "Her innovative 'coxcomb' polar area diagrams showed that preventable diseases caused far more deaths than combat. Her reforms reduced the death rate at Scutari Hospital from 42% to 2%, founding modern nursing and medical statistics.", "quizQuestion": "What type of innovative diagram did Florence Nightingale create?", "correctAnswer": "Coxcomb (polar area) diagrams", "distractors": ["Bar charts", "Pie charts", "Venn diagrams", "Line graphs"], "variants": [{"question": "By how much did Nightingale reduce the death rate at Scutari Hospital?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "From 42% to 2%", "distractors": ["From 80% to 50%", "From 20% to 10%", "From 60% to 30%"]}, {"question": "What did Nightingale prove was the main killer of soldiers?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Poor sanitation and preventable diseases", "distractors": ["Battle wounds", "Starvation", "Cold weather"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 4, "funScore": 8, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art hospital ward with a woman carrying a lamp walking between rows of beds, statistical charts pinned to the wall, clean white linens replacing dirty conditions.", "tags": ["history", "women-in-history", "scientific-revolutions", "medicine", "crimean-war"]}
{"id": "hist-fall-of-constantinople-206", "type": "fact", "statement": "The Fall of Constantinople on May 29, 1453, ended the Byzantine Empire when Ottoman Sultan Mehmed II breached the city's legendary walls.", "explanation": "Constantinople had withstood sieges for over 1,000 years. Mehmed used massive cannons — including the 8-meter 'Basilica' — to break the Theodosian Walls. The city became Istanbul, capital of the Ottoman Empire.", "quizQuestion": "What was the name of the massive cannon used to breach Constantinople's walls?", "correctAnswer": "The Basilica", "distractors": ["The Destroyer", "The Leviathan", "Big Bertha", "The Bombard"], "variants": [{"question": "Which Ottoman sultan conquered Constantinople?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Mehmed II", "distractors": ["Suleiman the Magnificent", "Bayezid I", "Osman I"]}, {"question": "What were the famous defensive walls of Constantinople called?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "The Theodosian Walls", "distractors": ["Hadrian's Wall", "The Aurelian Walls", "The Great Wall"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 3, "funScore": 8, "ageRating": "teen", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art massive city with domed buildings and a great cathedral, enormous cannon firing at crumbling stone walls, Ottoman soldiers swarming through a breach under siege towers.", "tags": ["history", "medieval", "famous-battles", "byzantine", "ottoman"]}
{"id": "hist-apollo-13-207", "type": "fact", "statement": "Apollo 13's crew survived a catastrophic oxygen tank explosion in 1970 by using the Lunar Module as a lifeboat for the 4-day return to Earth.", "explanation": "Commander Jim Lovell's famous words, 'Houston, we've had a problem,' began one of NASA's finest hours. Engineers on the ground improvised a CO2 scrubber from duct tape and cardboard to keep the crew alive in the cramped module.", "quizQuestion": "What did the Apollo 13 crew use as a lifeboat after the explosion?", "correctAnswer": "The Lunar Module", "distractors": ["An escape pod", "The Service Module", "A supply capsule", "The Command Module"], "variants": [{"question": "Who was the commander of Apollo 13?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Jim Lovell", "distractors": ["Neil Armstrong", "John Glenn", "Alan Shepard"]}, {"question": "What improvised device saved the Apollo 13 crew from CO2 buildup?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "A scrubber made from duct tape and cardboard", "distractors": ["A chemical filter", "An oxygen generator", "A ventilation fan"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 3, "funScore": 9, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art damaged spacecraft with a missing panel trailing debris in the blackness of space, the small Lunar Module glowing faintly, Earth visible as a distant blue dot.", "tags": ["history", "space-race", "nasa", "survival", "modern"]}
{"id": "hist-spanish-armada-208", "type": "fact", "statement": "The Spanish Armada of 1588 consisted of 130 ships sent by King Philip II to invade England, but was defeated by storms and English tactics.", "explanation": "The English fleet, commanded by Sir Francis Drake and Lord Howard, used fire ships and superior maneuverability against the larger Spanish galleons. Severe storms further devastated the fleeing Armada, with only about 67 ships returning to Spain.", "quizQuestion": "How many ships comprised the original Spanish Armada?", "correctAnswer": "130", "distractors": ["50", "500", "1,000", "300"], "variants": [{"question": "Which English commander helped defeat the Spanish Armada?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Sir Francis Drake", "distractors": ["Sir Walter Raleigh", "Lord Nelson", "Captain Cook"]}, {"question": "Approximately how many Spanish Armada ships returned to Spain?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "About 67", "distractors": ["All 130", "About 10", "None"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 3, "funScore": 8, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art dramatic naval battle scene with tall galleons exchanging cannon fire in rough seas, fire ships blazing, English and Spanish flags flying, dark storm clouds gathering.", "tags": ["history", "age-of-exploration", "famous-battles", "spain", "britain"]}
{"id": "hist-aztec-calendar-stone-209", "type": "fact", "statement": "The Aztec Sun Stone (Calendar Stone), carved around 1502, is a 3.6-meter basalt disc weighing 24 tonnes depicting the Aztec cosmological cycles.", "explanation": "The stone displays the five Aztec 'suns' (world ages), the current sun god Tonatiuh at center, and the 20 day signs of the sacred calendar. It was buried after the Spanish conquest and rediscovered in 1790 in Mexico City's main square.", "quizQuestion": "How much does the Aztec Sun Stone weigh?", "correctAnswer": "24 tonnes", "distractors": ["5 tonnes", "100 tonnes", "500 kg", "50 tonnes"], "variants": [{"question": "When was the buried Aztec Sun Stone rediscovered?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "1790", "distractors": ["1521", "1900", "1650"]}, {"question": "What is depicted at the center of the Aztec Sun Stone?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "The sun god Tonatiuh", "distractors": ["An eagle on a cactus", "The moon goddess", "A feathered serpent"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 4, "funScore": 8, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art massive circular stone disc with intricate carved concentric rings of symbols, a fierce sun face at center, displayed against a dark museum wall with dramatic lighting.", "tags": ["history", "ancient-civilizations", "aztec", "ancient-technology", "archaeology"]}
{"id": "hist-marie-curie-210", "type": "fact", "statement": "Marie Curie was the first person to win Nobel Prizes in two different sciences: Physics (1903) and Chemistry (1911).", "explanation": "Born in Poland, Curie discovered radioactivity with her husband Pierre, and isolated the elements polonium and radium. Her notebooks are still so radioactive they must be stored in lead-lined boxes and accessed with protective equipment.", "quizQuestion": "In which two scientific fields did Marie Curie win Nobel Prizes?", "correctAnswer": "Physics and Chemistry", "distractors": ["Biology and Physics", "Chemistry and Medicine", "Mathematics and Chemistry", "Physics and Medicine"], "variants": [{"question": "Which radioactive element did Marie Curie name after her home country?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Polonium", "distractors": ["Radium", "Francium", "Curium"]}, {"question": "Why are Marie Curie's notebooks still stored in lead-lined boxes?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "They are still radioactive", "distractors": ["They are extremely fragile", "They contain state secrets", "They are valuable antiques"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 2, "funScore": 9, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art laboratory with glowing vials of luminescent blue-green liquid, a woman scientist in a dark dress taking notes, scientific instruments and periodic table charts on the walls.", "tags": ["history", "women-in-history", "scientific-revolutions", "inventions", "nobel-prize"]}
{"id": "hist-bay-of-pigs-211", "type": "fact", "statement": "The Bay of Pigs invasion in April 1961 was a failed CIA-sponsored attempt by Cuban exiles to overthrow Fidel Castro's government.", "explanation": "About 1,400 exiles landed at the Bay of Pigs but were quickly defeated by Castro's forces within three days. The fiasco embarrassed the Kennedy administration and pushed Cuba closer to the Soviet Union, contributing to the Cuban Missile Crisis.", "quizQuestion": "How long did the Bay of Pigs invasion last before the exiles were defeated?", "correctAnswer": "About three days", "distractors": ["Two weeks", "One day", "Three months", "Two weeks"], "variants": [{"question": "How many Cuban exiles participated in the Bay of Pigs invasion?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "About 1,400", "distractors": ["About 10,000", "Roughly 200", "Over 50,000"]}, {"question": "Which US agency organized the Bay of Pigs invasion?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "The CIA", "distractors": ["The FBI", "The NSA", "The State Department"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 4, "funScore": 7, "ageRating": "teen", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art tropical beach at dawn with landing craft approaching through surf, armed men wading ashore, Cuban military vehicles visible beyond the palm tree line, fighter planes overhead.", "tags": ["history", "cold-war", "espionage", "cuba", "united-states"]}
{"id": "hist-gutenberg-bible-212", "type": "fact", "statement": "The Gutenberg Bible, printed around 1455, was the first major book produced with movable type in Europe, with only 49 copies surviving today.", "explanation": "Approximately 180 copies were printed, of which 49 survive (some incomplete). Each page has 42 lines, giving it the alternate name 'B42.' A complete copy sold at auction in 1987 for $5.39 million.", "quizQuestion": "How many copies of the Gutenberg Bible survive today?", "correctAnswer": "49", "distractors": ["3", "200", "1,000", "500"], "variants": [{"question": "How many lines per page does the Gutenberg Bible have?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "42", "distractors": ["30", "50", "66"]}, {"question": "Approximately how many Gutenberg Bibles were originally printed?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "About 180", "distractors": ["About 10", "Over 1,000", "Exactly 500"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 3, "funScore": 7, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art open illuminated book with ornate Gothic lettering on yellowed pages, gold leaf initials, displayed on a wooden lectern in a medieval scriptorium.", "tags": ["history", "inventions", "renaissance", "printing", "documents"]}
{"id": "hist-stonewall-riots-213", "type": "fact", "statement": "The Stonewall Riots of June 28, 1969, in New York City's Greenwich Village, are widely considered the catalyst for the modern LGBTQ+ rights movement.", "explanation": "When police raided the Stonewall Inn, a popular gay bar, patrons fought back in spontaneous protests lasting several days. The following year, the first Pride marches were held in New York, Los Angeles, San Francisco, and Chicago.", "quizQuestion": "In which New York City neighborhood did the Stonewall Riots occur?", "correctAnswer": "Greenwich Village", "distractors": ["Harlem", "Times Square", "Brooklyn Heights", "Midtown Manhattan"], "variants": [{"question": "In what year did the Stonewall Riots take place?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "1969", "distractors": ["1955", "1973", "1980"]}, {"question": "What event followed one year after the Stonewall Riots?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "The first Pride marches", "distractors": ["The Civil Rights Act", "Marriage equality", "Don't Ask Don't Tell"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 3, "funScore": 7, "ageRating": "teen", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art 1960s city street at night with a bar facade, a diverse crowd gathering with protest signs, police cars with flashing lights, neon signs reflecting off wet pavement.", "tags": ["history", "civil-rights", "united-states", "modern", "lgbtq"]}
{"id": "hist-zheng-he-voyages-214", "type": "fact", "statement": "Chinese Admiral Zheng He led seven massive naval expeditions (1405–1433) with fleets of up to 300 ships, reaching East Africa decades before European explorers.", "explanation": "Zheng He's treasure ships were up to 120 meters long — dwarfing Columbus's ships. His voyages established Chinese trade networks across Southeast Asia, India, the Persian Gulf, and East Africa, but the Ming Dynasty abruptly ended the program.", "quizQuestion": "How long were Zheng He's largest treasure ships?", "correctAnswer": "Up to 120 meters", "distractors": ["About 30 meters", "Roughly 50 meters", "Over 200 meters", "About 60 meters"], "variants": [{"question": "How many naval expeditions did Zheng He lead?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Seven", "distractors": ["Three", "Twelve", "Twenty"]}, {"question": "Which dynasty ended China's age of exploration after Zheng He?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "The Ming Dynasty", "distractors": ["The Qing Dynasty", "The Song Dynasty", "The Yuan Dynasty"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 4, "funScore": 9, "ageRating": "kid", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art massive Chinese junk ship with red sails and dragon prow leading a fleet of hundreds of ships across a turquoise ocean, African coastline visible on the horizon.", "tags": ["history", "age-of-exploration", "china", "silk-road", "naval"]}
{"id": "hist-nuremberg-trials-215", "type": "fact", "statement": "The Nuremberg Trials (1945–1946) were the first international war crimes tribunals, prosecuting 24 major Nazi leaders after World War II.", "explanation": "The trials established the principle that individuals — even heads of state — can be held personally responsible for crimes against humanity. Twelve defendants were sentenced to death, seven received prison sentences, and three were acquitted.", "quizQuestion": "How many major Nazi leaders were prosecuted at the Nuremberg Trials?", "correctAnswer": "24", "distractors": ["10", "50", "100", "12"], "variants": [{"question": "What legal principle did the Nuremberg Trials establish?", "type": "forward", "correctAnswer": "Individual criminal responsibility for crimes against humanity", "distractors": ["Diplomatic immunity", "National self-determination", "Freedom of the press"]}, {"question": "How many defendants were sentenced to death at Nuremberg?", "type": "reverse", "correctAnswer": "Twelve", "distractors": ["All 24", "Three", "None"]}], "category": ["history"], "difficulty": 3, "funScore": 7, "ageRating": "teen", "visualDescription": "A pixel-art imposing courtroom with rows of defendants in a dock, judges seated behind a raised bench, military police standing guard, bright lights illuminating the proceedings.", "tags": ["history", "wwii", "law", "modern", "war-crimes"]}
